##After two weeks as a security guard at the quarantine site, I got a fever

WMSYGSDR

Function introduction, each line has the earnest person, again the ordinary person also has the extraordinary story. Huazhong University of Science and Technology Press Official non-fiction story platform, the story of the people will meet here.

”

Since February, the new coronavirus epidemic situation is still serious, although we here are remote mountain areas, we have not been immune to the virus attack. The Golden Park Hotel has been used by the government as a central medical observation point for close contacts of people diagnosed with pneumonia.

Since February 2, the hotel has received more than 100 close contacts, who will be here for 14 days of medical observation. The observation point was staffed by personnel drawn from the departments of each town and divided into a coordination group, a logistics group, a medical group and a security group. The hotel also arranged a number of security guards, attendants and managers to work with the epidemic prevention and control.

1

Also on February 2, the downtown police station was tasked with the security of the medical observation point at the Golden Park Hotel.

At the meeting of the security team, the town's comrades repeatedly stressed that this security task is no joke. More than 100 people who were kept in isolation for observation had to stay in a separate room for 14 days. Who in their right mind could stand it, so someone could lose their temper at any moment, with incalculable consequences. The task of the security team is to ensure the personal safety of all personnel on observation and medical staff.

For the safety of my family, I went to the epidemic command to report, then I lived alone in a temporary residence not far from the observation point, consciously quarantined.

February 3rd, my first day on the job. I put on my work card issued by the headquarters and walked into the Golden Garden Hotel surrounded by a police cordon. With me in the same class were old Ding of the police station and two young patrol special police.

Our Place of work is in the hotel lobby on the first floor, at the entrance to check the identity of all people in and out of the hotel around the patrol, for suspicious persons and anomalies. The monitoring room is located on the east side of the hall. Security Guard Lao Li is on duty during the day. Lao Li is also responsible for disinfection inside and outside the hotel several times a day.

On This Day, the hotel received more than 60 observation staff, they were placed on the fourth floor to the eighth floor of the rooms, each individual room. All were told at the time of arrival that they would not be allowed to leave their rooms during quarantine to prevent cross-contamination.

I mean, it's just so cruel, that until yesterday, they were healthy, normal people, just like us, and all of a sudden, they're in strange rooms, confined like prisoners. If I were you, I'd be mad. But on second thought, how can the government stop the virus's frenzied advance without such extreme coercion?

We set up a table at the door to check in and out, and were issued only a box of disposable face masks and a thermometer. I wondered, shouldn't there still be alcohol, gloves, protective clothing and goggles?

The comrades of the Coordination Group explained that at present the materials are too scarce, and these things are given priority to medical personnel, and when the materials arrive, they will be distributed in full.

Knowing why, we stopped asking for things.

Ding and I were discussing whether we should wear one or two normal masks when the elevator door opened with a "Ding" and a man, wearing an N95, smiled at us and walked out the door.

This guy's a stranger. Shit! He doesn't work here.

"Wait! What are you doing? " I hurried to the front of a station, stopped him.

"I'm going out for a PACK OF CIGARETTES! " He replied in surprise.

"How did you get in here before? "

"I live here. They put me up here! "

"Are you a spectator here in quarantine? "

"Yes! "

The old Ding and two patrolmen all stood up suddenly, everybody all appeared very nervous at once. What's up with the medical team upstairs? I can't believe the quarantine just walked out!

Whatever the reason, I persuaded the man to go back and agreed to buy cigarettes for him. And report back immediately afterwards.

The instructor was informed of the situation and lost his temper in the working group. How did the management of the hotel do? Can't a quarantine officer just run around? Making Fun of the safety of the security staff?

The head of the medical team is also very aggrieved, they just took over the work today, busy from morning until now have not a drink of water, but there was such a major mistake. You can't blame the watcher. He's just been quarantined, and he's probably confused.

Finally is the security Lao Li stand out to take the blame, said to receive the notice to lock the elevator door and he forgot to lock.

Through this matter, we all realize the particularity of the work, can not be a bit careless. After all, this was our first quarantine mission, and no one had any experience, no one had any experience, not only with us, but even more so with the quarantined observers, who were more scared and anxious than we were. And who knows, maybe one day we'll be one of those segregated spectators.

Fourteen long days, for both of us is a severe test, only watch over each other, support each other in adversity, in order to have a common tomorrow.

In the afternoon, head nurse Xiao Zhao sent us five sets of secondary protective clothing, gave us a brief explanation of wear, finally told us, do not have to wear, because the remaining protective clothing is really not much.

2

On February 7, Dr. Li Wenliang died.

All Day Long, the circle of friends have been mourning Dr. Li's pictures and text screen, sad mood. At six o'clock in the evening, I took over the shift. It was dark earlier than usual. It seemed to rain. The road was deserted. The sprinklers had passed. The smell of disinfectant was in the air.

I lifted the cordon around the hotel and ducked through it, taking my temperature at the door. Ding arrived a little later than I did. His family lives in Jiangbei. Since the strict traffic control in the city, he has to walk more than an hour to work.

At first, the security team was relatively well staffed, but as the number of confirmed patients increased, so did the number of close contacts to be quarantined, and several nearby hotels were subsequently requisitioned by the government for medical observation and staffing became increasingly tight, the number of students per class was reduced to two. Fewer people, things are not rare, there are always impatient lonely onlookers to find something for us.

By the end of the day, there were more than 90 visitors in the hotel. Most of them were family members. Overnight, they went from living in groups to living alone. Their wives and husbands were separated by six or seven rooms. Their sons and mothers were separated by two or three floors.

The young boy could not help but want to visit the girl next door, however, every time the first signs together, he was caught in front of the monitoring screen, and then was promptly rushed to the medical staff to extinguish.

At night, the staff on duty locked the hotel lobby, and the hotel security Lao Wang on duty with the monitoring room.

The rain came down with the night. We were crammed into a tiny control room with three chairs, a small stove and a pot of boiling water to help us through the long night.

Their eyes were glued to the monitors, watching the medical team in Hazmat suits knock on the doors from the fourth to the eighth floor, taking the temperature of the room for the onlookers, the silent images echoing with the patter of rain outside the window, there is a sense of solemn, silent ritual. And pray for a safe night.

The good news from the medical team is that seven people are due for observation and will be tested for nucleic acid tomorrow. They will be able to leave as soon as their results are normal. The seven had been isolated in their homes for eleven days before they arrived, and we were relieved and pleased to learn that they were going home safe and sound.

I clicked on a list of items that the medical team had just sent out to the group, including books, stationery, snacks and more, that the support team was going to buy for the visitors tomorrow.

In order for them to live comfortably for the next 10 days, we are required to give them all their reasonable needs.

21:20, we have an anomaly.

Surveillance shows a man exiting room 706, walking down the hallway, talking on a cell phone. We quickly informed the medical staff that the man was still on the phone when the night shift of Dr. Chen and nurse Wang arrived on the seventh floor. Wearing protective clothing, Dr. Chen walked two meters away from him and said something to him, if I told him to go to his room right now.

The man did not cooperate.

The phone rang. It was nurse Wang. She explained the situation in a hurried voice. The man's wife was a suspected patient, but she had just been diagnosed at a designated hospital. The man was very emotional. He rushed to the hospital to take care of her.

This situation may not be dissuaded by the medical staff alone, I told nurse Wang not to panic, and Chen first try to stall him, but must pay attention to their own safety, I and old Ding immediately up. Now that his wife has been diagnosed, he's probably infected, too.

Old Ding and I were both wearing protective clothing for the first time, and the moment our feet slipped into the protective clothing, if we said we weren't afraid, that would be a lie. Security Guard Wang interjected when he went to open the elevator door, "Go up there, both of you, and if you get it, you'll all be killed. "

Lao Wang said, my heart "Dong Dong" beat two quitter, but I and old ding eye to eye, said in unison: "I go, you stay. "

Just then, nurse Wang called again, telling us not to go up. The man had calmed down after talking to his wife. Dr. Chen also patiently explained to him that his wife is only mild illness, will be safe. The man apologized for his behavior and went back to his room.

All clear. False alarm.

We folded the suit carefully, hoping we wouldn't get another chance to wear it tonight. I shook my head at the thought of the medical team in their Hazmat suits all day and all night, ashamed of the cowardice I had just developed.

3

At 22:30, we were notified that there were eight close contacts of confirmed patients in a neighbouring town (in a high mountain area) who needed to be moved overnight to our observation point.

We waited for more than three hours and nobody showed up. The Rain is getting heavier and heavier. I'm afraid it's snowing in the High Mountain area. Will there be no accident on the road? They were worried. There was a rumbling noise outside, and they finally arrived.

The AMBO and the police escort that were creeping in were covered with thick snow and ice, and they had chains that protected them from slipping. An ambulance brought the watchers into the hotel through the back door, where the medical team met them.

The four brothers in the police car got out of the car. As soon as I saw them all wet and muddy, shivering with cold, I told them to go inside and warm themselves.

It turned out that when they passed the 1,900-meter section of the road at sea level, the snow had made the road surface icy for several days. On an uphill section where one side was a cliff, the ambulance continued to slip on the ice surface and the anti-skid chain was worn off, the tyres were stuck in the muddy snow and could not go on.

It was a dangerous situation, so we had to push the car by hand, otherwise the ambulance would be in the back, and if we weren't careful, we'd be in the middle of a cliff. Four policemen pushed the ambulance together for half an hour, using their hands to support the ambulance as it climbed the long uphill section.

The handover of the quarantines was quickly completed, the water for the tea had not yet boiled, they were about to leave, I did not know their names, the night was too dark, I did not see their appearance, can only tell them to pay attention to safety, bon voyage.

The new stayer said the room was too cold. This can beat us, materials are so scarce, in the middle of the night where to find eight heaters, logistics group comrades in the Group spoke, "No problem, I am covered. "

We were skeptical, and the medical team was trying to do the work of the eight observers, getting them through the night and reconfiguring the furnace tomorrow.

Less than an hour later, there was another honking outside. A van pulled up to the hotel. The passenger's window was rolled open. Someone waved to us. It was the back office.

Hsiao-hsiang opened the carriage and filled it with heaters of various models. Small to see the problems reflected in the group, immediately through the phone to find a few of the city's electrical store manager, rushed to their warehouse, all the inventory of electric heaters have been moved here. I gave a thumbs-up to the small direction and said with a smile, "this is the speed of China! "

The following morning, the unquarantined visitors could go home. I thought they would leave without looking back, but I didn't expect to be asked to stay until after lunch, for no reason at all. The food was so good.

An uncle looked at us as he walked out of the hotel and said, "you have such dangerous jobs. How can you wear these masks? " He pulled out a pack of N95 masks from his bag and put them on the table at the door.

There is a little girl, insisted on her bag of snacks left to us, let us laugh and cry, but feel warm heart.

4

Two weeks later, the weather is still cold and warm, the first group of stay-at-home personnel will soon usher in the liberation, we all staff are very happy, the epidemic seems to have been effectively controlled.

But the night before the quarantine was lifted, there was bad news. One of the men began to have a fever. Maybe it's not all bad news, but if his symptoms had shown up a day later, they would have been released, and the consequences would have been far worse.

It happened that I was on the night shift again, and when I saw the name of the feverish patient, it struck me that it was the same man who, on my first day at work, had almost The Wrong Mans out to buy cigarettes?

Old Ding also found out, he stared at me and said, "the other day you face-to-face said so many words, you did not have it? "

I did not know at the time, thought to say: "should be all right, then wearing a mask, and then not confirmed it! "

Shortly after 8 pm, an ambulance from the county hospital arrived to pick up the patient with a fever, and the CDC had his room thoroughly disinfected.

It rained again at night, and the chill crept under the door into the house, and spring was slow to come. Old Ding and I took turns watching the midnight.

At three o'clock in the morning, I opened my eyes, replaced the old man, let him go to the next lounge to lie down.

Shortly before five o'clock, a man stepped into the lunar landscape, and a knock came at the door. When I opened the door, it was big sister Liu from the hotel kitchen, who started preparing breakfast for everyone at the observation point at this time of the day.

It was beginning to dawn, and the street was filled with sanitation workers. The hotel attendants are on duty. They put on protective clothing and start cleaning in the quarantine area.

I stretched, and suddenly there was a man in the sixth floor hallway of the quarantine zone. Zooming in on the Security Camera, I saw an elderly man with white hair sauntering up and down the aisle, ending up at the window of the stairwell, staring out of the window, motionless and seemingly lost in thought.

This must be an old man who used to get up early and go out for a walk. I glanced at the Monitor. The attendants had already cleared it to the fifth floor.

I have an impression of the old man, who was placed in quarantine yesterday because someone in his family had been diagnosed. I got his number from the quarantine list, but it went unanswered, and it looks like he left it in his room.

Shall I inform the medical staff on duty to persuade the old man to go back to his room? After all, they don't take off their Hazmat suits on duty. I gave up on the idea for a few seconds and let them sleep.

I'll have Lao Wang call the attendants, tell them not to go up to the sixth floor, and..
Walking across the street, he looked up through the building's many windows for the old man. He saw me first and waved to me. I held up a piece of cardboard with the words "please go to your room" written on it.

But the old man understood me at once. He nodded to me from afar and turned away.

Back to the control room, re-watch the screen, the old man really back room, I silently said a thank you to him. Is really a lovable, won't give the person trouble the old man, these days, can only condescend to you.

The CDC's medical staff arrived at the observation point at exactly seven o'clock each day to take throat swabs from the visitors, who came in and out of the hotel's back door quietly and quickly, one by one, heavily armed, and I couldn't see their faces. It used to be horrible to see something like this on TV, but now it's kind of Homey.

Less than eight o'clock, the day shift brothers came to take over, I went to wake up the old Ding, the day shift brothers to explain the situation last night, re-temperature ready to leave.

"Oh, don't go! " The kitchen elder sister came down with several hot breakfast boxes. "I'm afraid you're off duty. I cooked it for you in advance and ate it before leaving. "

I opened the breakfast box, is round dumplings, eat in the mouth soft Xiangtian.

5

When I got back to my house, I slept with my head covered and woke up just before one o'clock in the afternoon. When I sat up, I felt dizzy and tired all over. I felt a rush of panic. I didn't know what to do.

Did I really fall for that?

I suddenly remembered that my wife had put a cold medicine and a thermometer in my bag and found them at once, 37.8. For a moment, surprise, fear, anxiety, despair... heart blocked all kinds of taste.

I hesitated, called the instructor, and reported the situation. The instructor asked me carefully about the symptoms, told me not to panic, take cold medicine first, observation overnight.

I took the cold medicine with some trepidation, expecting a miracle to happen and everything to go back to normal. As a result, the body more and more uncomfortable, dizziness, body aches, to the evening, a day did not eat, also do not have a little appetite. Video-chatting with my family, afraid to tell them I have a fever, but my mother could tell at a glance that my face wasn't right, and under questioning, I told them the truth.

My mom was pretty sure it was the common cold, so don't beat yourself up about it. My daughter kept asking me in the video, "when are you coming back, Daddy? "

I answered with a wry smile: "to wait for the end of the epidemic, dad is now fighting the disease. " Daughter clenched his fist, a childish face shouted: "Dad, go! "

The encouragement and comfort of my family helped me settle down, and my body didn't feel so bad.

That night, out of a sweat, the next day the fever subsided, the body is still weak. I reported the situation to the instructor, who, just to be on the safe side, told me to stay home for a few more days, to isolate myself for observation.

These days have become the most leisurely days in my life, day sitting in the window reading clouds to see the sunset, at Night Nest in the Sofa watching drama, the time passed infinitely long. Trivial life experience and experience, by the daily collapse of boring bubble. I could really use a face-to-face.

At this point, I really understand the isolation of the viewer's mixed feelings.
To shake hands and hug everyone we meet, to kiss our wives and daughters on the face... how lucky we are compared to the lives taken in this epidemic. The virus is terrible, but what is more terrible is our indifference and slackness to the passing of life.

Things Change, life changes, live in the moment, it should be cherished. No matter how winter turns to spring, our best time is now.

(the characters use pseudonyms.)
